The current `adaptive_sort` implementation efficiently handles completely sorted and completely reverse-sorted arrays but falls back to a full `std::sort` for any other case, including "nearly sorted" data.

This improvement introduces a more nuanced "nearly sorted" detection using `std::is_sorted_until`. If only a small portion at the end of the array is unsorted (less than 1/16th of the array or 32 elements), it sorts only that portion and uses `std::inplace_merge` to combine it with the already-sorted prefix. This provides $O(N)$ or near-$O(N)$ performance for arrays with a large sorted prefix, while still correctly and efficiently handling fully sorted, reverse-sorted, and random data.

The threshold of `max(32, n/16)` ensures that for small arrays, we prefer a simpler sort-and-merge approach, while for large arrays, we only attempt the merge if the unsorted portion is relatively small. This maintains the high adaptability and performance scores of the previous version while improving efficiency for common nearly-sorted patterns.

